post_cb({"7460410": {"ViewCount": "932", "Body": "<p>From 4.1/2</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_7460410_7460410_0\">The value contained in the object indicated by the lvalue is the\n  rvalue result. When an lvalue-to-rvalue conversion occurs within the\n  operand of sizeof (5.3.3) the value contained in the referenced object\n  is not accessed, since that operator does not evaluate its operand.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Out of curiosity, I was wondering, does the same applies to the if, for, while statements, i.e lvalue is converted to rvalue when the result of statement is evaluated?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "7460424", "Title": "Lvalue to Rvalue conversions", "CreationDate": "2011-09-18T08:42:30.500", "Id": "7460410", "CommentCount": "0", "FavoriteCount": "2", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastActivityDate": "2011-09-18T09:10:46.920", "Score": "6", "OwnerUserId": "950393", "Tags": "<c++><lvalue-to-rvalue>", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_7460410_7460424_1": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.625, "section_id": 9}, "so_7460410_7460424_0": {"length": 8, "quality": 0.7272727272727273, "section_id": 7231}}, "n3337": {"so_7460410_7460424_1": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.625, "section_id": 6}, "so_7460410_7460424_0": {"length": 8, "quality": 0.7272727272727273, "section_id": 6975}}, "n4659": {"so_7460410_7460424_1": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.625, "section_id": 10}, "so_7460410_7460424_0": {"length": 8, "quality": 0.7272727272727273, "section_id": 8743}}}, "7460533": {"Id": "7460533", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>The answer is yes.</p>\n<p>When a bool rvalue is expected, the conversion also is applied. Let test be a variable to see an example:</p>\n<pre><code>if( test )\n</code></pre>\n<p>Rvalue of test, true or false, is evaluated inside the if.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2011-09-18T09:10:46.920", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2011-09-18T09:10:46.920", "ParentId": "7460410", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "887427"}, "7460424": {"Id": "7460424", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Yes. Without <code>lvalue-to-rvalue</code> conversion, it cannot read it's <em>value</em>.</p>\n<p>Loosely speaking, think of <em>lvalue</em> as some sort of container, and <em>rvalue</em> as the value contained in the container.</p>\n<p>C++03, section \u00a73.10/7 reads,</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_7460410_7460424_0\">Whenever an lvalue appears in a context where an rvalue is expected, the lvalue is converted to an rvalue; see 4.1, 4.2, and 4.3.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Read it along with, \u00a74.1/2 (your quotation),</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_7460410_7460424_1\">The value contained in the object indicated by the lvalue is the rvalue result.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Related topic:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/6376580/what-standard-clause-mandates-this-lvalue-to-rvalue-conversion\">What standard clause mandates this lvalue-to-rvalue conversion?</a></li>\n</ul>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "LastActivityDate": "2011-09-18T09:02:00.343", "Score": "7", "CreationDate": "2011-09-18T08:44:58.230", "ParentId": "7460410", "CommentCount": "2", "OwnerUserId": "415784", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T10:30:52.590"}});